---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import CopyPrompt from "../components/CopyPrompt.astro";

const setupPrompt = `Set up this repo to use srid/agency by following the instructions at
https://github.com/srid/agency/blob/master/docs/agency-setup.md`;

const year = new Date().getFullYear();
---

<BaseLayout title="agency">
  <article class="essay">
    <p class="wordmark">agency</p>

    <h1 class="display">
      <em>A loop you can leave alone.</em>
    </h1>

    <p class="lede">
      Two skills — <em>talk</em> for design and code exploration,
      <em>do</em> for shipping end&#8209;to&#8209;end. Drop them into Claude
      Code, Codex, or opencode, and the loop runs from research through
      structural review, CI, and merge — on every diff.
    </p>

    <CopyPrompt text={setupPrompt} />
    <p class="prompt-note">
      Run at the root of any repo. Detects an existing install and updates
      in place if you paste it again later. The whole workflow is on
      <a href="https://github.com/srid/agency" rel="noopener">GitHub</a>.
    </p>

    <h2 class="section"><em>Two entry points, never one.</em></h2>

    <p>
      <em>talk</em> and <em>do</em> are separate entry points, not steps in
      a single flow. Pick based on whether the spec is already clear.
    </p>

    <p>
      When the spec isn't obvious, reach for <em>talk</em> first. Discuss
      the approach, read code, sketch an interface, let <em>hickey</em> and
      <em>lowy</em> chew on the sketch. Read-only — no repo changes. Once
      you both converge on a plan, hand it to <em>do</em>.
    </p>

    <p>
      When <em>done</em> is concrete, reach for <em>do</em> directly:
      research, implement, structural review, quality gate, CI, ship. Each
      &ldquo;Fix in this PR&rdquo; finding lands as its own commit, so the
      history reads as a progression from primary implementation through
      each refinement.
    </p>

    <p>
      What <em>do</em> doesn't include is a design-exploration phase. Pasting
      a thin plan straight into <em>do</em> produces a thin implementation;
      the fix isn't to make <em>do</em> smarter, it's to do the design work
      in <em>talk</em> first.
    </p>

    <h2 class="section"><em>Feedback is the bottleneck.</em></h2>

    <p>
      The loop is only as good as its signal. If the agent can't tell whether
      its change actually worked, no amount of model capability papers over
      that gap. End-to-end tests are a prerequisite, not a nice-to-have —
      unit tests and type-checks alone aren't enough. What &ldquo;e2e&rdquo;
      means depends on the surface.
    </p>

    <p>
      For frontend work, screenshot evidence on every PR. First-class
      evidence as a workflow step is tracked in
      <a href="https://github.com/srid/agency/issues/106" rel="noopener">#106</a>.
    </p>

    <p>
      For Nix-based infrastructure, NixOS VM tests. Honest tradeoff: a VM
      isn't a live environment, mocking is often required, and reaching real
      fidelity for non-trivial infra takes effort — but it's still the
      closest thing to an executable spec the agent can drive.
    </p>

    <p>
      For backend and library code, fast and deterministic e2e suites the
      agent can run in a tight loop. Slow or flaky suites destroy the loop;
      a thirty-second deterministic run beats a ten-minute thorough one.
    </p>

    <h2 class="section"><em>State, within and across.</em></h2>

    <p>
      Within a single PR, <em>do</em> writes per-step lifecycle, status, and
      timing to <em>.do-results.json</em> at the repo root. The
      <em>do-stop-guard</em> Stop hook reads this so the agent can't bail
      mid-workflow — if a run is still <em>working</em>, stops are blocked
      until it reaches <em>done</em> or is explicitly marked <em>failed</em>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Across PRs, no built-in memory, by design. Scope each PR small enough
      to land end-to-end in a day or two. Branches that linger longer are a
      smell — break the work down further.
    </p>

    <p>
      When work genuinely doesn't fit in one PR, have <em>talk</em> produce
      a GitHub issue with explicit phases, then run <em>do</em> against each
      phase as its own PR. The issue is the cross-PR memory.
      <a href="https://github.com/juspay/kolu/issues/514" rel="noopener"
        >juspay/kolu#514</a
      > is the worked example.
    </p>

    <h2 class="section"><em>On reviews of structure.</em></h2>

    <p>
      Type-checkers, tests, and CI catch correctness; they don't catch
      design. An LLM-generated diff can pass every automated gate and still
      complect two roles into one construct, or draw a module boundary along
      the wrong axis of change.
    </p>

    <p>
      <em>do</em> closes that gap with two structural-review passes that run
      post-implement on the concrete diff, in parallel:
      <em>hickey</em> for accidental complexity, after Rich Hickey's
      <em>Simple Made Easy</em>; <em>lowy</em> for volatility-based
      decomposition, after Juval Lowy's
      <em>Righting Software</em> (building on Parnas, 1972). Each finding
      lands as its own commit. The full ledger is posted as a PR comment.
    </p>

    <p>
      Read
      <a href="https://kolu.dev/blog/hickey-lowy/" rel="noopener"
        >Hickey/Lowy on kolu.dev</a
      > for the full framing — what each lens looks for and why the pair
      catches what tests miss.
    </p>

    <h2 class="section"><em>In motion.</em></h2>

    <div class="video">
      <iframe
        src="https://www.youtube-nocookie.com/embed/IFp0bb2D0ZE?start=426&rel=0"
        title="agency walkthrough — adding a /code-police rule"
        loading="lazy"
        allow="accelerometer; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture"
        referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin"
        allowfullscreen></iframe>
    </div>
    <p class="caption">Adding a <em>/code-police</em> rule, in real time.</p>

    <h2 class="section"><em>In the wild.</em></h2>

    <p>
      <a href="https://kolu.dev" rel="noopener">Kolu</a> — a terminal-native
      cockpit for coding agents — is the canonical adopter. See its
      <a
        href="https://github.com/juspay/kolu/blob/master/apm.yml"
        rel="noopener">apm.yml</a
      > and
      <a href="https://github.com/juspay/kolu/tree/master/.apm" rel="noopener"
        >.apm/</a
      > for how project-specific instructions layer on top of the generic
      workflow.
    </p>

    <hr class="coda-rule" />

    <blockquote class="coda">
      <p>
        Pure intent is a palpable life-force; an actually occurring stream of
        benevolence and benignity that originates in the vast and utter
        stillness that is the essential character of the universe itself.
        With pure intent running as a <span class="gold">golden thread</span>
        through one's life, reflective contemplation about being here doing
        this business called being alive rapidly becomes more and more
        fascinating.
      </p>
    </blockquote>
    <p class="coda-attrib">
      — Richard,
      <a
        href="https://actualfreedom.com.au/richard/abditorium/pureintent.htm"
        rel="noopener">on pure intent</a
      >.
    </p>

    <p class="colophon">
      <a href="https://github.com/srid/agency" rel="noopener"
        >github.com/srid/agency</a
      > · mit · {year}
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
